07243nam a22012495i 9780691215082DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211997nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912150827 a10.1515/97806912150822doi  a(DE-B1597)563267  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBL820.M37bM43 1997eb 7aREL0720002bisacsh04a292.2/1322200aMedea :bEssays on Medea in Myth, Literature, Philosophy, and Art /ced. by James J. Clauss, Sarah Iles Johnston. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b5 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPREFACE -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I: MYTHIC REPRESENTATIONS -- t1 Medea, the Enchantress from Afar: Remarks on a Well-Known Myth -- t2 Corinthian Medea and the Cult of Hera Akraia -- t3 Medea as Foundation-Heroine -- t4 Why Did Medea Kill Her Brother Apsyrtus? -- tPART II: LITERARY PORTRAITS -- t5 Medea as Muse: Pindar's Pythian 4 -- t6 Becoming Medea: Assimilation in Euripides -- t7 Conquest of the Mephistophelian Nausicaa: Medea's Role in Apollonius' Redefinition of the Epic Hero -- t8 The Metamorphosis of Ovid's Medea -- tPART III: UNDER PHILOSOPHICAL INVESTIGATION -- t9 Medea among the Philosophers -- t10 Serpents in the Soul: A Reading of Seneca's Medea -- tPART IV: BEYOND THE EURIPIDEAN STAGE -- t11 Medea at a Shifting Distance: Images and Euripidean Tragedy -- t12 Medea as Politician and Diva: Riding the Dragon into the Future -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tLIST OF CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX LOCORUM -- tGENERAL INDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the dawn of European literature, the figure of Medea--best known as the helpmate of Jason and murderer of her own children--has inspired artists in all fields throughout all centuries. Euripides, Seneca, Corneille, Delacroix, Anouilh, Pasolini, Maria Callas, Martha Graham, Samuel Barber, and Diana Rigg are among the many who have given Medea life on stage, film, and canvas, through music and dance, from ancient Greek drama to Broadway. In seeking to understand the powerful hold Medea has had on our imaginations for nearly three millennia, a group of renowned scholars here examines the major representations of Medea in myth, art, and ancient and contemporary literature, as well as the philosophical, psychological, and cultural questions these portrayals raise. The result is a comprehensive and nuanced look at one of the most captivating mythic figures of all time. Unlike most mythic figures, whose attributes remain constant throughout mythology, Medea is continually changing in the wide variety of stories that circulated during antiquity. She appears as enchantress, helper-maiden, infanticide, fratricide, kidnapper, founder of cities, and foreigner. Not only does Medea's checkered career illuminate the opposing concepts of self and other, it also suggests the disturbing possibility of otherness within self. In addition to the editors, the contributors include Fritz Graf, Nita Krevans, Jan Bremmer, Dolores M. O'Higgins, Deborah Boedeker, Carole E. Newlands, John M. Dillon, Martha C. Nussbaum, Christiane Sourvinou-Inwood, and Marianne McDonald.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh  aAegeus.  aApsyrtus.  aBattus and Battiads.  aBoreas.  aChalciope.  aChryssipus.  aCreon (of Corinth).  aCyrene.  aDelphi.  aDemonax.  aDioscuri.  aEgypt.  aEumelus.  aEuphamus.  aGalen.  aHecate.  aHelen.  aLamia.  aLemnian women.  aLibya.  aLilith.  aMedeus (Medus).  aMormo.  aNeophron.  aPeliades.  aPhilomela.  aPhrixus.  aProcris.